// Citations and quotes:
//
// Standish Group, CHAOS Report 2020: Beyond Infinity (2020):
//   Statistics: 31% of projects successful (on time, budget, full scope); 50% challenged
//   (late, over budget, or reduced scope); 19% failed outright. Combined: 69% fail or are
//   challenged. Dataset: 16,000+ projects. Note: the "66%" figure circulates from 1990s
//   editions — use 69% for the 2020 report specifically.
//
// Fred Brooks, "The Mythical Man-Month" (Addison-Wesley, 1975):
//   Brooks's Law: "Adding manpower to a late software project makes it later."
//   On how lateness accumulates: "How does a project get to be a year late?
//   One day at a time."
//   — Identifies the structural failure mode: each small slip goes unaddressed until a
//   year is gone, and the proposed fix (add people) actively makes things worse.
//
// Daniel Kahneman, "Thinking, Fast and Slow" (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2011), Ch. 23:
//   "The planning fallacy is that you make a plan, which is usually a best-case scenario.
//   Then you assume that the outcome will follow your plan, even when you should know better."
//   — Names the cognitive mechanism: optimistic best-case thinking is the structural default,
//   not a correctable mistake.
//
// Bent Flyvbjerg & Dan Gardner, "How Big Things Get Done" (Crown Currency, 2023):
//   "Over budget, over time, under benefits — over and over again." (the "iron law")
//   Statistics from 16,000-project database: only 8.5% of projects meet both cost and
//   schedule targets; only 0.5% achieve cost, time, AND benefits targets. Mean IT cost
//   overrun: 73%. For severely over-budget IT projects, average overrun: 447%.

#let title = [Rarely Delivered on Time, Budget, or Scope]

#let body = [
Software projects fail at a rate that would be considered catastrophic in any other engineering discipline.
Cost overruns, schedule slippage, and scope reduction are not edge cases — they are the norm.
This is not primarily a failure of talent or effort; it is a failure of the structures teams use to reason about what they are building and how long it will take.

The root cause is a planning process that treats each project as unique, when the evidence from decades of project data says the opposite: failure modes are predictable, the biases that produce bad estimates are universal, and the disciplines that improve outcomes are known and teachable.
]
